Tired of corruption
My friend Boris was about to leave my house, drunk.
I therefore suggested that he not drive.
He asked me why.
"you've been drinking," I said, "aren't you afraid of the police?"
Boris replied: "No, I have a document featuring Benjamin Franklin; it's always useful."
He showed me his driver's license with the $100 bill slipped beside it.
Of course, I knew that the police took bribes, but I was worried that Boris would meet a policeman who wasn't corrupt.
« Impossible », said Boris, « to enter the traffic police force, you must buy your chief's silence. »
If you don't take bribes, how can you buy your boss's silence?
Half of the drivers in Moscow use illegally purchased driver's licenses.
The fools who try to do things by the book drown in administrative hassles.
"For 100 dollars, you can drive into the city without brakes!"
Corruption and embezzlement have always existed in Russia, before and after Lenin's October Revolution.
But never at the record levels we see today.
Everyone accepts bribes, everywhere and for everything.
The only ones who don't accept them are those to whom they are not offered, according to Boris.
Corruption thrives in most institutions, and the fight against corruption always ends in a catastrophe or abandonment.
The police, prosecutors, customs officials, and even the Kremlin: no one, anywhere, is immune.
Recently, I was visiting a dacha village in one of the most beautiful suburbs of Moscow.
It was a lush place but similar to the gulag with its high-security fences and guards.
Looking at the pretentious houses decorated with such little taste, I wondered who owned them and heard myself answer that one belonged to an assistant mayor of Moscow, another to a famous singer, and yet another to the son of the prosecutor of Moscow.
But the most attractive property belonged to a modest tax office employee.
Corruption now poses a greater threat to Russia than the Chechen war.
In fact, the Chechen war would not have lasted as long if it had not been conducted by corrupt generals, officers, civil servants, and police officers who sell weapons and supplies to the rebels.
Recently, Russian television showed a bus shuttling between Grozny and Moscow, the same bus that transported the 120 kilograms of explosives used during the siege of the Dubrovka theater, where so many victims perished during the assault aimed at freeing the hostages.
A bus passenger covered the explosives with a cloth soaked in acid to prevent the customs dogs from detecting them.
A quite useless precaution.
No one controls the buses today.
The driver, who didn't know what he was transporting, said he was stopped 50 times along his journey, always for the same reason.
A police officer was coming to ask him, "Do you know the price?" and the driver would reply, "Of course, I know it," and pay the bribe before leaving.
Without a bribe, the bus would have been delayed for hours at each stop, which would have amounted to entire days for the entire trip.
The war against Chechnya continues without end not only because the Chechen rebels have as allies Al-Qaeda and all the "international terrorist network," but also because Russian corruption is their ally.
The police, the army, civilians who accept bribes, and thieves who first extort the Chechen civilians or simply steal their belongings, sell weapons and explosives to terrorists, provide maps indicating the locations of minefields, and supply rebels with forged documents.
In May of this year, during the Kaspiisk explosions, terrorists used weapons purchased from Russian army officers.
The rebels have modern weapons.
Where do they come from?
In the mountains where the rebels hide, there are no gun shops.
But the 80,000 Russian soldiers fighting the rebels do have ammunition stocks, from which weapons are stolen and sold.
And not only weapons: some young officers sell their own men into slavery.
Russian corruption has reached catastrophic levels, yet no fight has been launched against this plague.
Punish corruption more severely?
That would only increase the cost of corruption.
The harsher the punishment, the more it will cost to avoid it.
No official wants to fight corruption because they themselves are corrupt.
Thus, those who are called "simple people" regard this phenomenon with benevolence.
They say of their mayor, "Of course, he's corrupt, but look at all he's done for the city!"
Ordinary people also don't like honest workers.
Why?
A train ticket costs 100 rubles, but by paying a small bribe, one can travel for 50 rubles.
The traveler and the controller both benefit from this system.
An honest old grandmother once told me that she had bought a ticket and tried to board the train.
The conductor had stopped her by telling her that passengers with a ticket were not allowed on the train!
For millions of Russians, corruption is a normal way of life.
If you don't want your son to be called for military service, buy a soldier's clerk and he will remove your son's name from the list, or bribe a doctor to declare him unfit for any military activity.
You can enter any faculty for a certain price, regardless of your references and diplomas.
You can drive drunk, speed, ignore red lights, as long as Ben Franklin is there to offer himself to the police.
Alexander Menchikov, the minister of Peter the Great, had understood the impossibility of winning the fight against corruption.
When Tsar Peter, disgusted by the corruption in Russia, decided to hang his corrupt officials, Menchikov replied: "Your Majesty, you risk losing all your subjects."
In the centuries that have passed since then, the situation has worsened.
Eliminating corruption might leave the state without citizens, but if we do not stop the spread of corruption, citizens will soon be left without a state.
